'''World Literacy Crusade''' (WLC) is a non-profit organisation formed in 1992 by the Rev. Alfreddie Johnson to fight [[Literacy|illiteracy]],<ref>World Literacy Crusade [http://www.worldliteracy.org World Literacy Crusade] -- homepage for WLC (accessed 2007-02-21)</ref> and supported by the [[Church of Scientology]].<ref name=JRL09>{{cite book|last1=Lewis|first1=James R.|title=Scientology|date=2009|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=9780199715954|page=9|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=MtW90YkkB3gC&pg=PA9|accessdate=10 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=Ham12>{{cite book|last1=Lewis|first1=James R.|editor1-last=Hammer|editor1-first=Olav|editor2-last=Rothstein|editor2-first=Mikael|title=The Cambridge Companion to New Religious Movements|date=2012|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9781107493551|page=137|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=RM0AAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA137|accessdate=10 November 2015}}</ref> The group uses [[Study Tech|"study technologies"]] and [[Purification Rundown|"drug rehabilitation technologies"]] developed by [[L. Ron Hubbard]], the Church's founder.<ref>{{cite web | first = Joseph | last = Mallia | title = Church keys programs to recruit blacks | url = http://www.apologeticsindex.org/s04a04.html | work = Inside the Church of Scientology | publisher = [[Boston Herald]] | date = 1998-03-02 | accessdate = 2008-03-18 }}</ref><ref name="Scientology probes">{{cite web | first = Jim | last = MacLaughlin |author2=Gully, Andrew  | title = Church of Scientology probes Herald reporter - Investigation follows pattern of harassment | url = http://www.apologeticsindex.org/s04a12.html | work = [[Boston Herald]] | date = 1998-03-19 | accessdate = 2008-03-18 }}</ref> It has been characterized as a "Scientology front group",<ref name=Breitb04>{{cite book|last1=Breitbart|first1=Andrew|last2=Ebner|first2=Mark|title=Hollywood, interrupted : insanity chic in Babylon - the case against celebrity|date=2004|publisher=Wiley|location=Hoboken, N.J.|isbn=9780471450511|page=128|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=20AnywIUix4C&pg=PA128|accessdate=10 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=smith13>{{cite book|last1=Smith|first1=Ronald D.|title=Strategic planning for public relations|date=2013|publisher=Routledge|location=New York|isbn=9781136172489|page=209|edition=4th|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=f4STAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA209|accessdate=10 November 2015}}</ref> and has been promoted by [[Celebrity Centres|celebrity Scientologists]] such as [[Isaac Hayes]] and [[Anne Archer]].<ref name=JRL09 />

==Controversies==
The LA Times reported in 2008 that about 100 protestors gathered outside of the World Literacy Crusade offices after being sold fake low cost housing vouchers for as much as $1500. Officials at WLC admitted to selling the free vouchers, but stated they did not know they were fake.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2008/03/many-people-are.html|title=Renters in search of affordable housing get scammed|date=2008-03-21|website=LA Times Blogs - L.A. NOW|language=en-US|access-date=2016-08-27}}</ref> The Compton, Californian offices of the WLC housed a drug detox program using “dry heat sweat therapy”.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cironline.org/reports/rehab-operators-fight-reopen-clinics-criminal-pasts-come-light-5592|title=As rehab operators fight to reopen clinics, criminal pasts come to light  {{!}} The Center for Investigative Reporting|website=cironline.org|access-date=2016-08-27}}</ref> In 2015 the executive director of WLC, Hanan Islam and her adult children were arrested for  Medi-Cal fraud and insurance fraud for billing for this detox program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://socialcult.com/2016/04/11/scientologys-disappearing-front-groups-applied-scholastics/|title=Scientology’s Disappearing Front Groups: Applied Scholastics|last=Socialcult|date=2016-04-11|website=Scientology - The Social Cult|access-date=2016-08-27}}</ref>

